04785nam a22007335i 9780231519939DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2009012521  a(OCoLC)979739606  a97802315199397 a10.7312/wals148322doi  a(DE-B1597)459423  a(OCoLC)643070880  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBQ6160.C6bW35 2009 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a294.3/65709512221 aWalsh, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSacred Economies :bBuddhist Monasticism and Territoriality in Medieval China /cMichael Walsh. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b24 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Sheng Yen Series in Chinese Buddhist Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tDynastic Chronology -- t1. Monastic Identity, Buddhist Religiosity, and Land -- t2. A Square at the Center of the World -- t3. Corporate Bodies -- t4. A Culture of Estates -- t5. Grains of Sand -- t6. Cultivating Salvation -- t7. Salvation and Survival -- tAppendix A. Yin County Buddhist Monastic Land, c. 1226 c.e. -- tAppendix B. Population Figures for Yin County, Ming Prefecture -- tAppendix C. Land Totals in Ming Prefecture -- tAppendix D. Major Structures in Tiantong Monastery’s Compound -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBuddhist monasteries in medieval China employed a variety of practices to ensure their ascendancy and survival. Most successful was the exchange of material goods for salvation, as in the donation of land, which allowed monks to spread their teachings throughout China. By investigating a variety of socioeconomic spaces produced and perpetuated by Chinese monasteries, Michael J. Walsh reveals the "sacred economies" that shaped early Buddhism and its relationship with consumption and salvation.Centering his study on Tiantong, a Buddhist monastery that has thrived for close to seventeen centuries in southeast China, Walsh follows three main topics: the spaces monks produced, within and around which a community could pursue a meaningful existence; the social and economic avenues through which monasteries provided diverse sacred resources and secured the primacy of Buddhist teachings within an agrarian culture; and the nature of "transactive" participation within monastic spaces, which later became a fundamental component of a broader Chinese religiosity. Unpacking these sacred economies and repositioning them within the history of religion in China, Walsh encourages a different approach to the study of Chinese religion, emphasizing the critical link between religious exchange and the production of material culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBuddhismxEconomic aspectszChina. 0aBuddhist monasteriesxEconomic aspectszChina. 0aMonastic and religious life (Buddhism)zChina. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/wals1483240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231519939423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231519939/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-de